# Creating New Pages

## Route architecture

| Route file            | URL pattern          | Behavior                                    |
|-----------------------|----------------------|---------------------------------------------|
| `index.astro`         | `/`                  | Fetches Sanity page with slug `"home"`      |
| `[[slug]].astro`      | `/<anything>`        | Optional catch-all; fetches page by slug    |

Both use `loadQuery` from `src/sanity/lib/load-query.ts` to fetch data.

## Adding a Sanity-driven page

Most pages are created in Sanity Studio, not as new `.astro` files. The `[[slug]].astro` route handles any slug automatically.

1. In Sanity Studio, create a new Page document
2. Set a slug (e.g., `about`, `contact`)
3. Add modules to the page
4. Publish — the page is immediately available at `/<slug>`

## Adding a static route

For pages that don't come from Sanity (e.g., a blog index, legal page):

1. Create `src/pages/<name>.astro`
2. Import `Layout` from `../layouts/Layout.astro`
3. Import `loadQuery` if you need Sanity data (e.g., site settings for nav/footer)
4. Wrap content in `<Layout>` with `title` and `description` props

## Page template pattern

```astro
---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { loadQuery } from "../sanity/lib/load-query";
import { SITE_SETTINGS_QUERY, type SITE_SETTINGS_QUERY_RESULT } from "../sanity/queries";
import { Navigation } from "../components/layout/Navigation";
import { Footer } from "../components/layout/Footer";

const { data: siteSettings } = await loadQuery<SITE_SETTINGS_QUERY_RESULT>({
  query: SITE_SETTINGS_QUERY,
});
---

<Layout title="Page Title">
  <Navigation client:load links={siteSettings?.navigation?.links} />
  <main>
    <!-- page content -->
  </main>
  <Footer {...siteSettings?.footer} />
</Layout>
```

## SSR rules

- The site runs SSR via Cloudflare adapter — pages are rendered on every request
- No `getStaticPaths()` needed; dynamic params resolve at request time
- `[[slug]].astro` double brackets make the slug **optional** (undefined at `/`)
